\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 This document is to build a website for Brendan Scoggin\'92s professional growth and portfolio.\
\
\
Initial instructions to point the Wordpress domain to the GitHub repository:
\f1\b0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 To point a domain purchased through WordPress.com to a GitHub Pages repository, you essentially need to change who "handles" your traffic. Since WordPress.com is primarily a hosting platform, they don't provide a way to "pull" code from GitHub into their servers. Instead, you will host the code on GitHub and tell your domain to look there.\
Here is the step-by-step process to bridge the two.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 \strokec2 1. Prepare your GitHub Repository\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 Before touching your domain settings, ensure your GitHub repository is ready to serve as a website.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 In your GitHub repo, go to 
\f0\b Settings
\f1\b0  > 
\f0\b Pages
\f1\b0 .\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Under 
\f0\b Build and deployment
\f1\b0 , ensure your source is set to "Deploy from a branch" (usually the \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 main\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  or \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 master\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  branch).\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 In the 
\f0\b Custom domain
\f1\b0  section, type in your domain (e.g., \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 www.yourdomain.com\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 ) and click 
\f0\b Save
\f1\b0 . This creates a \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 CNAME\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  file in your repository.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 \strokec2 2. Configure DNS at WordPress.com\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 Now you need to tell WordPress.com to send visitors to GitHub's servers.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Log in to your 
\f0\b WordPress.com dashboard
\f1\b0 .\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Go to 
\f0\b Upgrades
\f1\b0  > 
\f0\b Domains
\f1\b0 .\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Click on the domain you want to use and select 
\f0\b DNS records
\f1\b0  > 
\f0\b Manage
\f1\b0 .\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Remove existing records:
