\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 \strokec2 3. Verify and Secure (HTTPS)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 DNS changes can take anywhere from a few minutes to 24 hours to "propagate" across the internet.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Back in your 
\f0\b GitHub Repository Settings
\f1\b0  > 
\f0\b Pages
\f1\b0 , look for the "DNS check" status.\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Once the DNS check passes, check the box for 
\f0\b Enforce HTTPS
\f1\b0 . This ensures your site is secure.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 \strokec2 Important Distinction\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 By doing this, you are using WordPress.com only as a 
\f0\b Domain Registrar
\f1\b0 . You will no longer be using the WordPress site builder or their hosting for this specific domain. All your website updates will now be managed by \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 git commit\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  and \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 git push\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  to your GitHub repository.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

